# Security Guidelines for Goravel

## Input Validation
- Validate all user inputs using request classes
- Implement proper sanitization for user data
- Use whitelist validation where possible
- Validate file uploads thoroughly
- Implement CSRF protection for forms

## Authentication & Authorization
- Use secure password hashing (bcrypt, scrypt)
- Implement proper session management
- Use JWT tokens for API authentication
- Implement role-based access control (RBAC)
- Use middleware for route protection

## Database Security
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement proper database permissions
- Use database encryption for sensitive data
- Implement audit logging for data changes
- Use connection pooling securely

## API Security
- Implement rate limiting for API endpoints
- Use HTTPS for all communications
- Implement proper CORS policies
- Use API keys and tokens securely
- Implement request/response logging

## File Upload Security
- Validate file types and sizes
- Scan uploaded files for malware
- Store files outside web root
- Implement proper file permissions
- Use secure file naming conventions

## Environment Security
- Never commit secrets to version control
- Use environment variables for sensitive data
- Implement proper secret management
- Use different configurations for different environments
- Implement proper logging without exposing secrets

## Dependency Security
- Keep dependencies updated
- Use dependency scanning tools
- Implement proper dependency management
- Use trusted package sources
- Monitor for security vulnerabilities

## Infrastructure Security
- Use Docker security best practices
- Implement proper container scanning
- Use secure base images
- Implement network security policies
- Use proper secret management in containers

## Monitoring & Incident Response
- Implement security monitoring
- Log security events appropriately
- Implement incident response procedures
- Use security scanning tools
- Implement proper backup and recovery procedures